Human papillomavirus DNA in surgical smoke
procedures and its impact on the surgeon
This article was published in the following Dove Press journal:
The purpose of this study was to explore whether human papillomavirus (HPV)
DNA is present in surgical smoke generated by loop electrosurgical excision procedures
(LEEPs). Furthermore, we investigated the impact of this HPV DNA on surgeons.
A total of 134 outpatients with persistent HPV infections treated with LEEP for
cervical intraepithelial neoplasia between 2015 and 2016, along with the corresponding
uorescence in situ hybridization technique was
used to detect HPV DNA in exfoliated cervical cells from the patients, in surgical smoke and
in nasal epithelial cells from the surgeons before and after LEEP.
The positive rates of HPV DNA in the three types of samples mentioned above
were 94.8%, 29.9% and 1.5%, respectively. The distribution of HPV subtypes in surgical
smoke was identical to that in the cervical specimens. The positive rate of HPV DNA in
cantly increased for greater distances of the suction device from
the surgical site. The nasal epithelial cells of two surgeons were positive for HPV DNA, and
the genotypes were consistent with those in the corresponding surgical smoke. After a
6-month follow-up, the nasal swabs from these two doctors tested negative for HPV DNA.
This study demonstrated the presence of HPV DNA in surgical smoke
produced by LEEP and the risk of airborne transmission of HPV DNA during the operation.
Fortunately, the HPV DNA in the nasopharynx of the operators was not persistent.
